  accentWord="Gas"
  subhead="You post four photos of a back boiler conversion in a 1970s semi in Kidlington. Photo one: the before — a Baxi Bermuda Inset 2 back boiler behind a gas fire in the lounge, the open-flue terminal barely visible behind the fireplace surround, the ancient programmer wired into the dining room wall. Photo two: the strip-out — back boiler disconnected and removed, the fireplace opening visible showing the old asbestos rope seal and crumbling firebrick, gas supply capped at the meter, flue liner removed from the chimney. Photo three: the new installation — a Worcester Bosch Greenstar 8000 Style 30 combi mounted in the kitchen utility cupboard, horizontal concentric flue exiting through the external wall with a plume management kit, 22mm copper flow and return to the existing radiator circuit, MagnaClean Pro2 filter on the return, condensate to the kitchen waste trap, tado° Wireless Smart Thermostat mounted in the hallway. Photo four: the completed kitchen — boiler neatly enclosed in the cupboard, pipework boxed in, the tado° displaying 21°C, and the Benchmark certificate on the worktop beside a cup of tea. Seventy-eight likes, nine shares. A homeowner in Botley messages: 'We have the exact same Bermuda back boiler behind our gas fire! It is from 1978. The pilot light goes out every week and the heating barely works. We want a modern combi like yours in our kitchen. Our house is a 1970s semi, three bedrooms, one bathroom, ten radiators. The gas fire is original — we will close the fireplace up. What would this cost roughly? Can you come and look?' You are commissioning a boiler. Without AI Messenger, the Bermuda conversion waits. With it, the AI confirms your back boiler conversion experience, asks about the chimney condition and whether the fireplace is structural, and captures: Botley 1970s 3-bed semi, Baxi Bermuda Inset 2 from 1978, pilot out weekly, kitchen combi conversion, fireplace closure, 10 radiators, survey request."
  scenario="It is 10:30pm on a Friday in January. A homeowner in Witney messages: 'Evening — our boiler just stopped. Vaillant ecoTEC pro 24 showing an F.75 fault code — we looked it up and it says something about the water pressure sensor. No heating, no hot water. House temperature dropping — it is freezing outside. We have a 6-month-old baby. Can someone come first thing Saturday morning? If the boiler needs replacing it is 12 years old and we have been thinking about it anyway — want quotes for a Vaillant or Worcester around 28-30kW. Three beds, one bathroom, eight radiators.' Without AI Messenger, the freezing family waits until Saturday morning calls. With AI Messenger, the response at 10:31pm: 'Thank you — F.75 is typically a water pressure sensor fault which can sometimes be resolved with a sensor replacement. Could you confirm the pressure gauge reading and whether the boiler has lost pressure recently?' She confirms pressure at 1.2 bar, no pressure loss. Saturday 8am you attend: Witney, Vaillant ecoTEC pro 24, F.75 pressure sensor, 12yr, 3-bed 1-bath 8 rads, baby, repair or replacement quote Vaillant/Worcester 28-30kW."
  benefits={benefits}
